g from the lone pairs of the carbonyl oxygen via a through-space peri-interaction. This leads to the proposed structure. The unusual coupling pattern of this signal might arise from long-range couplings to fluorine or across the selenium atom.\n\nThe evidence strongly supports this structure, and no further experiments seem necessary to determine the constitution.\n\nFINAL_RESULT:\n  UUID: b621abf2-8442-4135-a641-13b7a344dd5f\n  PREDICTED_SMILES: COc1ccc(CSeC2=CC=CC=C2C(=O)C(F)(F)F)cc1\n  CONFIDENCE: 0.95\n  REASON_BRIEF: The structure was determined by assembling key fragments identified from NMR data: a p-methoxybenzyl group, a trifluoroacetyl group, and a disubstituted benzene ring linked by a selenium atom. The exceptionally deshielded proton at 10.46 ppm is a hallmark of a peri-interaction between the proton and the carbonyl oxygen, confirming the ortho-substitution pattern.",
